FILL_CH12 = {
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>Herod Agrippa I's persecution of the church — killing James and imprisoning Peter — is the third wave of official opposition in Acts (after the Sanhedrin's actions in chs. 4-5 and the Hellenist persecution of ch. 8). The Christological pattern: persecution intensifies precisely as the mission expands. The same Passover season that brought Christ's death now brings James's death — the apostolic community begins to share in Christ's own passion-pattern. 'If they persecuted me, they will also persecute you' (John 15:20) is being fulfilled in real time.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The execution of James son of Zebedee is the first apostolic martyrdom recorded in Acts. Jesus had predicted it: 'Can you drink the cup I am going to drink?' — James and John answered yes (Matt 20:22-23); Jesus confirmed 'you will indeed drink my cup'. James is the fulfillment of that prophecy — the first of the Twelve to drink Christ's cup in full. The Christological witness: martyrdom is not mission failure but the completion of the testimony. James's blood is the seedbed of the Jerusalem church's continued growth.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Herod imprisoned Peter during the days of Unleavened Bread — the Passover season. The Christological irony: the same feast that commemorated the first Exodus and that framed Jesus's crucifixion is now the occasion for an attempt to eliminate his chief apostle. The Passover timing is deliberate (v. 4 — 'after the Passover he intended to bring him out'). The persecutor who seizes God's people at Passover puts himself in the position of Pharaoh; the subsequent rescue will be Exodus-shaped.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Peter guarded by four squads of four soldiers — sixteen guards total — with the intention of public execution after Passover. The Christological parallel: the Romans placed guards at Jesus's tomb (Matt 27:65-66) to prevent the body from being removed; now Herod places sixteen guards on Peter to prevent escape. In both cases, the human precaution against divine action is futile. Maximum security cannot contain the one who has the key of David (Rev 3:7 — 'who opens and no one will shut').</p>",
    "5": "<p>'So Peter was kept in prison, but earnest prayer (<em>proseuchē de ēn ektenōs ginomenē</em>) for him was being made to God by the church.' The contrast is between the prison (Herod's instrument) and prayer (the church's instrument). The Christological community's response to crisis is prayer — not political action, not armed resistance, but intercession directed to the God who raised Jesus from the dead. The earnestness (<em>ektenōs</em> — stretched out, intense) echoes Jesus's Gethsemane anguish (Luke 22:44 — 'praying more earnestly').</p>",
    "6": "<p>Peter sleeping between two soldiers the night before his expected execution — 'and he was sleeping' (<em>ēn de ho Petros koimōmenos</em>) — is itself a Christological testimony. The apostle facing death sleeps peacefully, trusting the God who raised Jesus from the dead. The Christological echo: Jesus slept during the storm (Luke 8:23) while the disciples panicked; Peter's sleep before his execution is the resurrection faith made physical — death has been defanged, the sting removed (1 Cor 15:55). Trust in the risen Christ enables sleep in the face of death.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The angel's sudden appearance, light in the cell, the striking of Peter's side (<em>pataxas de tēn pleuran tou Petrou</em>) — the physical urgency of the rescue mirrors the Exodus pattern (the angel struck Egypt before Israel's deliverance). The chains falling from Peter's hands parallels Luke 4:18 (Jesus's mission: 'proclaim liberty to the captives, the opening of prison to those who are bound'). Christ's mission statement is being enacted through his apostle's rescue: the prisoner set free is the gospel made visible.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The angel's detailed instructions — wrap your cloak, put on your sandals, follow me — emphasize Peter's groggy, barely awake state: he does not engineer his own escape but follows step-by-step divine instruction. The Christological disciple-pattern: the follower of Christ is rescued not through cleverness but through obedience to the divine guide. Peter 'did not know that what was being done by the angel was real' (v. 9) — he follows instructions even without full comprehension, trusting the guide.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Peter follows the angel out, thinking he was seeing a vision (<em>edokei horama blepein</em>) — the boundary between vision and reality is characteristically fluid in Acts' divine encounters. The Christological significance: the resurrection itself was questioned on the same terms (were the appearances visions?). Peter's subsequent realization that the deliverance was real (v. 11) is the same structure as the disciples' recognition that the risen Christ was not a ghost but real (Luke 24:36-43 — 'Handle me and see; for a spirit hath not flesh and bones').</p>",
    "10": "<p>Passing the first guard, the second guard, and the iron gate that opened by itself (<em>automatē</em>) — the self-opening iron gate is the climax of the Exodus-rescue imagery. Ps 107:16 ('he has broken the gates of bronze and cut in two the bars of iron') is the psalm of divine deliverance from imprisonment and darkness. The risen Christ who holds 'the keys of Death and Hades' (Rev 1:18) opens iron gates before his apostle as readily as he opened his own tomb.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Now I am sure that the Lord has sent his angel and rescued me from the hand of Herod and from all that the Jewish people were expecting' — Peter's recognition of the divine rescue is a confession of Christ's lordship over political power. The Lord who sent his angel to deliver is the risen Jesus who 'has gone into heaven and is at the right hand of God, with angels, authorities, and powers having been subjected to him' (1 Pet 3:22). The rescue is not luck but the exercise of Christ's cosmic authority over the powers that oppose his mission.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Peter's arrival at Mary's house where the church was gathered in prayer is the answer to the intercession of v. 5 arriving in person. The Christological community had been praying for Peter's release; they were still praying when he arrived. The prayer-and-answer structure confirms Christ's promise: 'Ask, and it will be given to you' (Matt 7:7). John Mark's presence connects this Jerusalem church scene to the first missionary journey about to unfold in chapter 13.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Rhoda recognizing Peter's voice but failing to open the gate in her excitement — running back to report instead — is a charming narrative detail that establishes the humanness of the community. The Christological community is not composed of superhuman believers but ordinary people whose reactions include confusion, disbelief, and excitement. The risen Christ works through genuinely human instruments, with all their hesitations and surprises intact.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Rhoda's report is met with a flat response: 'You are out of your mind' (<em>mainomai</em>). The disbelief of the community toward the answer to their own prayer — they have been praying all night for Peter's release, and when told he is at the door, they say Rhoda is crazy — is a gentle Lukan rebuke and a pattern-match: the disciples had not believed the women's resurrection report (Luke 24:11 — 'these words seemed to them an idle tale'). Faith in Christ does not eliminate the human tendency to disbelieve the very answers we have prayed for.</p>",
    "15": "<p>When Rhoda insisted, they shifted explanations: 'It is his angel' — the folk belief that a person's guardian angel (cf. Matt 18:10) could appear was apparently more credible to the praying community than that Peter himself was free. The Christological irony: they accepted the supernatural (an angelic appearance) more readily than the historical (the actual man). The resurrection encounters in the Gospels follow the same inversion — the disciples accepted apparition (Luke 24:37) before they accepted embodied reality.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Peter continued knocking until they finally opened and saw him — his persistence mirrors his Lord's invitation: 'knock, and it will be opened to you' (Matt 7:7). The astonishment of the gathered community when they see Peter in the flesh echoes the disciples' amazement at the resurrection appearances. Every miraculous deliverance in Acts is a small resurrection: the man who was effectively dead (condemned to execution) stands alive before the praying community.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Peter's signal for silence, recounting of the escape, and instruction to 'tell James and the brothers' establishes the Jerusalem church's leadership transition. James (the Lord's brother) has emerged as the Jerusalem anchor; he will preside at the Jerusalem Council (15:13-21). The Christological succession: the first James (son of Zebedee) has been martyred; the second James (brother of Jesus) leads the community. Christ's community endures the loss of leaders by raising up new ones — the pattern of resurrection applied to community leadership.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The soldiers' consternation over Peter's disappearance mirrors the soldiers' confusion at the empty tomb (Matt 28:4 — 'the guards trembled for fear of him and became like dead men'). Both guards — at the tomb and at the prison — find the one they were securing gone without explanation. The Christological pattern: divine power exercised through resurrection (empty tomb) and through resurrection-shaped rescue (empty cell) leaves the same bewilderment in those who rely on human force alone.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Herod's ordered execution of the guards mirrors Pharaoh's pattern of punishing his servants when divine rescue defeated his plans. The Christological point: worldly power, when it cannot contain the resurrection community, turns its violence inward. The tyrant's inability to defeat Christ's mission destroys the tyrant's own administration. Herod's departure from Judea to Caesarea is the beginning of his trajectory toward the divine judgment of vv. 21-23.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The Herod-Tyre-Sidon quarrel — the coastal cities seeking peace because they depended on Herod's territory for food — sets up the court scene. The Christological backdrop: as the church intercedes and God delivers (vv. 5-17), the persecutor is involved in mundane political disputes that will occasion his downfall. The sovereign God who rescues Peter is the same sovereign who orchestrates the historical circumstances surrounding every persecutor's ultimate fall.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Herod's royal robe and public oration — the occasion apparently a reconciliation with the Tyrian and Sidonian delegations — becomes the moment of his judgment. The pomp that surrounds him (<em>esthēta basilikēn</em>, royal garments) is the platform for the crowd's acclamation: 'The voice of a god, and not of a man!' The Christological contrast: Jesus, the actual God incarnate, was stripped, mocked, and crucified in humiliation; Herod, a human pretender to divine honor, is dressed in glory and receives divine acclamation — and is immediately destroyed for accepting it.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The crowd's acclamation — 'The voice of a god, and not of a man!' (<em>theou phōnē kai ouk anthrōpou</em>) — is the perennial temptation that Herod fails: receiving for himself the honor that belongs to God. The Christological contrast is stark: when the crowd tried to make Jesus king (John 6:15), he withdrew; when Cornelius fell at Peter's feet in worship, Peter said 'Stand up; I too am a man' (Acts 10:26). The Christ and his servants consistently refuse divine honor; the persecutor of Christ's people accepts it and is destroyed.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Immediately an angel of the Lord struck him down, because he did not give God the glory, and he was eaten by worms and breathed his last.' The divine judgment is swift, total, and Christologically significant. The one who killed James (Christ's apostle) and planned to kill Peter is killed by the same angelic power that rescued Peter. The Christological justice: those who oppose the mission of the risen Lord encounter the risen Lord's sovereign judgment. The worm-eaten death echoes the Isaianic description of the enemies of God's people (Isa 66:24 — 'their worm shall not die').</p>",
    "24": "<p>A theme: 'But the word of God increased and multiplied' (<em>ho de logos tou theou ēuxanen kai eplēthyneto</em>) — the contrast summary after Herod's death is one of Luke's six growth statements (6:7; 9:31; 12:24; 16:5; 19:20; 28:31). The persecutor is dead; the word grows. The Christological inversion: every attempt to suppress the gospel of the risen Christ results in its expansion. The pattern is cross-shaped: what looks like setback produces growth; what appears as defeat is the mechanism of victory.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Barnabas and Saul return from Jerusalem, having completed their famine-relief mission (11:27-30), bringing John Mark with them. The quiet transition verse connects the Jerusalem church (ch. 12) to the Antioch church (ch. 13) and sets up the Spirit's commissioning of the first missionary journey. John Mark's presence anticipates the Barnabas-Paul split of 15:36-41 and his later restoration (2 Tim 4:11 — 'he is very useful to me for ministry'). The Christological community includes those who fail and are restored as well as those who succeed from the start.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH13 = {
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>The Antioch church's prophets and teachers are listed before the Spirit's commissioning of Barnabas and Saul. The Christological significance: the first intentional missionary sending originates not in Jerusalem but in this multiethnic, Hellenistic community — the Spirit is not bound to the established center but moves where the Christological community worships and listens. The list itself (Barnabas, Simeon Niger, Lucius of Cyrene, Manaen, Saul) is the most ethnically diverse leadership body in Acts.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'While they were worshipping the Lord (<em>leitourgountōn de autōn tō kyriō</em>) and fasting, the Holy Spirit said: 'Set apart for me Barnabas and Saul for the work to which I have called them.' The Spirit's voice during worship and fasting is the Christological commission for the Gentile mission. The missionary call does not arise from strategic planning but from attentive listening during worship directed to the Lord Jesus. Christ commissions through his Spirit what he commanded in his ascension: witness to the ends of the earth.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The laying on of hands and sending away — the Antioch church's liturgical act of commissioning — is the community's participation in what the Spirit has initiated. The Christological pattern: the Spirit calls, the community confirms. Neither acts independently. The sending is simultaneously the Spirit's (<em>ekpemphthenotes hypo tou hagiou pneumatos</em>, v. 4 — 'sent out by the Holy Spirit') and the church's. Missionary authority flows through both divine commission and community confirmation.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'So, being sent out by the Holy Spirit, they went down to Seleucia, and from there they sailed to Cyprus' — the Spirit's sending connects directly to Christ's commission (1:8 — 'you will be my witnesses'). Cyprus is Barnabas's home territory (4:36); the Spirit's routing begins where the missionary has natural connections. The Christological wisdom: the Spirit works through the apostles' existing relationships and backgrounds, not despite them. The gospel uses the human network the Spirit shaped before the commission was given.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Salamis synagogue proclamation — 'they proclaimed the word of God in the synagogues of the Jews' — establishes the first-journey pattern: beginning with the synagogue audience that has the scriptural foundation for receiving the Christological argument. John Mark as assistant (<em>hypēretēs</em>) parallels Jesus's own pattern of sending disciples out in pairs (Luke 10:1). The Christological mission strategy: start with those who have the prophetic preparation, then extend to those without it.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The encounter with Bar-Jesus ('son of Jesus/Joshua') — a Jewish false prophet and magician — at the court of Sergius Paulus places Paul before a high-ranking Roman official with a counterfeit guide. The Christological irony of the name: 'Bar-Jesus' (son of the Savior) is the designation of a man who actively opposes the true Jesus. The spiritual battle is for the soul of the proconsul; the false prophet is the agent of the 'god of this world who has blinded the minds of unbelievers' (2 Cor 4:4).</p>",
    "7": "<p>Sergius Paulus 'summoned Barnabas and Saul and sought to hear the word of God' (<em>epezētēsen akousai ton logon tou theou</em>) — the Roman proconsul's genuine intellectual and spiritual openness is the occasion for the encounter. The Christological mission reaches into the highest levels of Roman administration. Christ's promise that his witnesses would stand before 'governors and kings' (Matt 10:18; Acts 9:15) is being fulfilled systematically as the mission advances from synagogues to palaces.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Elymas the magician 'withstood them, seeking to turn the proconsul away from the faith' — the Christological conflict is explicit: this is not merely a personal dispute but a contest over whether Sergius Paulus will move toward or away from faith in the risen Christ. Every conversion is a transfer of sovereignty: from the domain of the false to the domain of the true Lord. The opponent of conversion is simultaneously an opponent of Christ's lordship over his own created image-bearer.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'But Saul, who was also called Paul, filled with the Holy Spirit, looked intently at him' — the first use of the name Paul in Acts marks the Roman mission's beginning. The Spirit-filling for this specific confrontation (the Spirit acts situationally, not merely permanently) grants discernment and authority. The 'intent gaze' (<em>atenisas</em>) is the same focused attention Peter used before healing the lame man (3:4) — the prelude to a decisive act in Christ's name.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'You son of the devil, you enemy of all righteousness, full of all deceit and villainy, will you not stop making crooked the straight paths of the Lord?' — Paul's denunciation identifies Elymas with the adversarial power that opposes Christ's mission. 'Making crooked the straight paths of the Lord' echoes Isa 40:3-4 (the highway-preparation prophecy applied to John the Baptist, Luke 3:4-5) — Elymas is doing the opposite of John's preparatory work. Where John straightened the way for Christ, Elymas curves it. The Christological mission has its counterfeit counter-mission.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The blindness judgment on Elymas — 'immediately mist and darkness fell on him' — is a temporary blindness mirroring Paul's own Damascus road blindness (9:8-9). The Christological irony: Paul was blinded on the road to Damascus when Christ revealed himself; Elymas is blinded when he tries to prevent Christ's revelation reaching another. The same risen Christ who struck Paul blind to open his eyes (9:17-18) strikes Elymas blind through Paul. The judgment is Christologically administered.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Sergius Paulus believed, 'astonished at the teaching of the Lord' (<em>ekplēssomenos epi tē didachē tou kyriou</em>) — the Roman proconsul's conversion is described as astonishment at the Lord's teaching, not merely at the miracle of blinding. The Christological priority: the miracle prompts attention; the teaching produces faith. The sign is the servant of the word; the word about the risen Lord is what creates belief. The first Gentile conversion on the first missionary journey is a Roman official who is 'astonished at the teaching of the Lord.'</p>",
    "13": "<p>Paul and his companions sailed from Paphos to Perga in Pamphylia, where John Mark departed and returned to Jerusalem. The desertion of John Mark is the event that will cause the Barnabas-Paul split in 15:36-41. The Christological community experiences internal conflict and failure as well as external opposition — neither the mission's divine commissioning nor its apostolic leadership prevents the ordinary human tensions that test every partnership.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Arriving at Pisidian Antioch and going into the synagogue on the Sabbath — the missionary pattern repeats: Sabbath, synagogue, opportunity to speak. The Christological witness seeks the prepared soil first. The synagogue audience has the Scriptures that Paul's sermon will open; the reading of the Law and the Prophets (v. 15) provides the canonical framework within which the Christological proclamation makes sense. The message is new but not discontinuous — it fulfills what the audience already reveres.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The synagogue rulers' invitation — 'Brothers, if you have any word of encouragement (<em>logos paraklēseōs</em>) for the people, say it' — provides Paul his opening. The Christological word is simultaneously proclamation and consolation: the gospel of the risen Christ is the supreme word of encouragement (<em>paraklēsis</em>) that fulfills what the Law and the Prophets promised. The synagogue's liturgical hospitality becomes the occasion for the most developed Pauline sermon in Acts.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Paul's gesture — standing up and motioning with his hand — mirrors the classical orator's stance. His address to 'Men of Israel and you who fear God' identifies his dual audience: ethnic Jews and God-fearing Gentiles who had been attending synagogue. The Christological mission strategy targets both simultaneously: those who have the full covenant background and those who have come partway. Both groups are prepared differently but will receive the same Christological proclamation.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'The God of this people Israel chose our fathers and made the people great during their stay in the land of Egypt, and with uplifted arm he led them out of it' — Paul's survey of Israel's history begins with Exodus because the Christ-event is the new and greater Exodus. The same pattern that structured Stephen's speech (ch. 7) structures Paul's: Israel's history is the preparation for Christ. The 'uplifted arm' that brought Israel out of Egypt is the same divine power that raised Jesus from the dead.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'And for about forty years he put up with them in the wilderness' — the forty years of patient divine endurance during the wilderness period is the type of Christ's patience with a failing people. The same God who sustained Israel through its failure in the wilderness (Exod 16:35; Num 14:33-34) is the God who sustained the community of Jesus through the repeated failures of the disciples. Divine patience is the Christological mode of God's relationship with the covenant community through history.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The destruction of the Canaanite nations and Israel's inheritance of the land (citing Josh 14:1) — seven nations destroyed over approximately 450 years — establishes God's pattern: promise, delay, fulfillment. The Christological typology: the inheritance of the land under Joshua prefigures the inheritance of the nations under Jesus (same name: <em>Iēsous/Yehoshua</em>). What Joshua accomplished for Israel in Canaan, Jesus accomplishes for the new Israel in the world.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The period of judges through Samuel — the leadership sequence from conquest to monarchy — traces the covenant community's governance before the Davidic kingship. The Christological survey: God's patience through the cyclical failure of judges (Judg 2:11-19) is the pattern of divine faithfulness despite human unfaithfulness, culminating in the Davidic covenant whose ultimate fulfillment is Christ. Every judge is a provisional deliverer pointing toward the permanent king.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Saul the Benjaminite given as king, then rejected — the irony for the speaker (Saul of Tarsus, also a Benjaminite) is not subtle. The Christological reading of Saul's kingship: it was Israel's demand for 'a king like the nations' (1 Sam 8:5), not God's initiative. The subsequent giving of David ('a man after my heart', v. 22; 1 Sam 13:14) contrasts the human-selected and divinely-selected king. Christ is the ultimate fulfillment of the divine-selection pattern: not Israel's demand but God's own appointment.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'I have found in David the son of Jesse a man after my heart, who will do all my will' — the Davidic testimony (combining 1 Sam 13:14 and Ps 89:20) is Paul's bridge to the Christological announcement. David is the type because he is 'after God's heart' — the one whose will aligns with God's. Jesus is the antitype: the one who perfectly does 'not my will, but yours' (Luke 22:42 — the Gethsemane surrender). The one whose will perfectly aligned with the Father's is the one David's kingship anticipated.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'From his offspring God has brought to Israel a Savior, Jesus, as he promised' — the programmatic Christological declaration arrives after the patriarchal-Davidic survey: the entire history was prologue to this. The Savior from David's offspring fulfills the Davidic covenant's deepest promise (2 Sam 7:12-16; Ps 89:3-4; Ps 132:11). Paul's Christological announcement is not an innovation but the completion of what every Jewish worshipper had been waiting for through the entire canonical history he has just rehearsed.</p>",
    "24": "<p>John's preparatory baptism of repentance — 'before his coming' (<em>pro prosōpou tēs eisodou autou</em>, before the face of his entry) — establishes the Baptist as the forerunner whose ministry defines what preceded Christ. The Christological significance of John's place: he is the last prophet of the old order, the final voice before the one he announced. Paul's citation of John's testimony is both apologetic (Jewish audiences knew the Baptist) and theological (the forerunner validates the Coming One).</p>",
    "25": "<p>John's own self-testimony — 'What do you suppose that I am? I am not he. No, but behold, after me one is coming, the sandals of whose feet I am not worthy to untie' — is Paul's citation of the Baptist's Christological humility. John, the greatest of the prophets (Luke 7:28), claims himself unworthy of the most servile act toward Jesus. The Christological principle: every prophet and every servant exists to point beyond themselves to Christ. Authentic ministry is always self-diminishing and Christ-magnifying.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Brothers, sons of the family of Abraham, and those among you who fear God, to us has been sent the message of this salvation' — the Christological word of salvation addresses both Jew (sons of Abraham) and God-fearer (Gentile) simultaneously. The 'message of salvation' (<em>ho logos tēs sōtērias tautēs</em>) is a Lukan summary for the gospel of the risen Christ. The salvation announced is specific (this salvation — referring to everything the survey of history was building toward) and universal in address (to us — both covenant heirs and attached Gentiles).</p>",
    "27": "<p>'For those who live in Jerusalem and their rulers, because they did not recognize him nor understand the utterances of the prophets that are read every Sabbath, fulfilled them by condemning him' — the Christological irony of the crucifixion: those who heard the prophets every Sabbath but did not understand them fulfilled those very prophecies by their misunderstanding. The passion was simultaneously the greatest crime (deliberate miscarriage of justice) and the greatest fulfillment (every Sabbath's readings accomplished). God's purposes run through, not around, human blindness and malice.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'Though they found in him no guilt worthy of death, they asked Pilate to have him executed' — the fourfold innocence declaration pattern (Pilate three times, Herod once in Luke's Gospel) that Luke has established is summarized here: Jesus was condemned without just cause. The Christological apologetic: the crucifixion was not the exposure of a criminal but the execution of an innocent. God's pattern of vindicating the righteous sufferer (Ps 22; 69; Isa 53) required first the unjust condemnation that the resurrection would reverse.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'When they had carried out all that was written of him, they took him down from the tree and laid him in a tomb' — 'all that was written' (<em>hapanta ta peri autou gegrammena</em>) is Paul's comprehensive claim: the entire passion narrative fulfilled scriptural prophecy. The 'tree' (<em>xylon</em>) citation echoes Deut 21:23 ('cursed is everyone who hangs on a tree') — Paul will develop this explicitly in Gal 3:13. The burial ('laid him in a tomb') establishes the death as real and verifiable: witnesses saw the body placed, which makes the subsequent resurrection appearance the more evidentially powerful.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'He appeared for many days to those who had come up with him from Galilee to Jerusalem, who are now his witnesses to the people' — the post-resurrection appearances to the Galilean companions are the evidentiary foundation of Paul's proclamation. The witnesses 'who are now his witnesses to the people' are the contemporary Jerusalem community (the Twelve and the 500+ of 1 Cor 15:6) who can still be interrogated. The Christological testimony is historically verifiable in principle: the witnesses are alive and the testimony is current.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'And we bring you the good news that what God promised to the fathers, this he has fulfilled to us their children by raising Jesus' — the resurrection is the fulfillment-event that all the promises pointed toward. The Christological gospel is simultaneously the continuation of Israel's story (what God promised to the fathers) and the event that consummates it (raising Jesus). Paul is not announcing a departure from Israel's hope but its arrival. The promise-fulfillment structure makes the gospel the completion of the canonical narrative, not its replacement.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Ps 2:7 applied to the resurrection — 'You are my Son; today I have begotten you' — is Paul's first OT proof text for the resurrection. The 'today' of the psalm is interpreted as the resurrection day: the day the Father publicly declared Jesus to be his Son by raising him from the dead (cf. Rom 1:4 — 'declared to be the Son of God in power according to the Spirit of holiness by his resurrection from the dead'). The coronation psalm's royal declaration is the resurrection's theological content.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Isa 55:3 ('I will give you the holy and sure blessings of David') — the second OT proof. The 'holy and sure blessings' (<em>ta hosia Dauid ta pista</em>) are permanent covenant mercies that death cannot revoke. Paul's argument: these promises were made to David but could not be fulfilled in David (who died); they require a Davidic descendant who does not see corruption. The resurrection makes the Davidic blessings permanent and universal — available to 'everyone' (v. 39) rather than restricted to ethnic Israel.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Ps 16:10 ('you will not let your Holy One see corruption') — the third OT proof, the same psalm Peter used at Pentecost (2:27-31). Paul's application: David died, was buried, and saw corruption; therefore the psalm's promise is not about David but about the one David prophetically described. The resurrection is the historical event in which God kept the promise to his Holy One — the tomb was empty, the body was not subject to decomposition. The convergence of three independent OT witnesses to the same event is Paul's cumulative proof-by-Scripture.</p>",
    "36": "<p>'For David, after he had served the purpose of God in his own generation, fell asleep and was laid with his fathers and saw corruption' — the finality of David's death is Paul's crucial distinction. David was 'the man after God's heart' who 'served the purpose of God in his own generation' — and yet he died and his body decayed. The Christological argument: if David fulfilled God's purpose but still died, the Psalms he wrote that speak of no-corruption must refer to someone else. The typological gap between David and his greater son requires the resurrection to fill it.</p>",
    "37": "<p>'But he whom God raised up did not see corruption' — the resurrection is the fact that distinguishes Jesus from every previous righteous sufferer and fulfills every promise-without-precedent in the OT. No one before Jesus had been raised to immortal resurrection life; everyone else who was raised (Lazarus, Jairus's daughter) died again. Jesus's resurrection is categorically different: a once-for-all transformation into imperishable life. This is the event that validates the entire Christological reading of Israel's Scripture.</p>",
    "38": "<p>'Let it be known to you therefore, brothers, that through this man forgiveness of sins is proclaimed to you' — the Christological implications of the resurrection-proclamation are soteriological: the one God raised is also the one through whom sins are forgiven. The resurrection vindicates Christ's atoning death; the forgiveness flows from the completed work of the one God raised. The forensic claim — God raised the one who bore sin's penalty — is the basis for the offer of forgiveness to everyone who believes.</p>",
    "39": "<p>'And by him everyone who believes is freed from everything from which you could not be freed by the law of Moses' — the Christological superiority claim: the law of Moses could not free; Christ does. <em>Dikaioō</em> (justified, freed, acquitted) is the Pauline term for the forensic standing before God that the law could not provide (cf. Rom 3:20-26; Gal 2:16). The 'everyone' (<em>pas ho pisteuōn</em>) is the universal-scope claim: not restricted to covenant members but available to all who believe. This is the Pauline gospel in its Acts form.</p>",
    "40": "<p>'Beware, therefore, lest what is said in the Prophets should come about: 'Look, you scoffers, be astounded and perish; for I am doing a work in your days, a work that you will not believe, even if one tells it to you'' — the Habakkuk citation (Hab 1:5) is a warning that divine acts exceed human expectation and cannot be dismissed. The Christological urgency: the resurrection is 'a work you will not believe, even if one tells it to you' — the category-breaking event that human expectation cannot contain. Dismissal of the resurrection is the fulfillment of the prophetic warning against scoffing at divine action.</p>",
    "41": "<p>The citation ends with Habakkuk's warning of perishing for those who refuse to believe God's astonishing work. The Christological offer is simultaneously a Christological warning: the same resurrection that offers forgiveness and justification to believers announces judgment for those who reject it. Christ crucified is 'a fragrance from life to life' for some and 'from death to death' for others (2 Cor 2:15-16) — the response to the Christological proclamation determines its effect.</p>",
    "42": "<p>As Paul and Barnabas left the synagogue, the people — both Jews and devout converts — asked them to speak again the next Sabbath. The Christological reception: the first preaching created desire for more. The gospel of the risen Christ is its own most effective apologetic — it raises questions it also answers, creates hunger it is designed to satisfy. The invitation to return is the Spirit's own work in the hearts of those who heard.</p>",
    "43": "<p>After the meeting broke up, many Jews and devout proselytes followed Paul and Barnabas, who urged them 'to continue in the grace of God' (<em>prosmenein tē chariti tou theou</em>). The pastoral follow-up is Christologically grounded: the grace in which new believers are urged to remain is the grace embodied in the crucified-and-risen Lord. Perseverance in grace is perseverance in Christ — not mere doctrinal assent but ongoing orientation toward the one in whom grace is personally encountered.</p>",
    "44": "<p>The following Sabbath, almost the whole city gathered to hear the word of the Lord — the scale of the response demonstrates the gospel's appeal across the entire social spectrum of Pisidian Antioch. The Christological word draws the city to itself. The 'word of the Lord' (<em>ton logon tou theou</em>) is the message about the risen Jesus; when proclaimed faithfully, it generates its own audience. The Spirit who raised Christ from the dead is the same Spirit who draws the cities of the world toward the proclamation of that resurrection.</p>",
    "45": "<p>When the Jews saw the crowds they were filled with jealousy and began contradicting what Paul said, blaspheming (<em>blaspēmountes</em>). The Christological conflict: the success of the proclamation provokes the opposition. This is the pattern that recurs in every city: initial openness, then synagogue resistance when the scale of Gentile response threatens the established community's identity. The blasphemy against the Christological proclamation is the most serious form of rejection in Acts.</p>",
    "46": "<p>'It was necessary that the word of God be spoken first to you. Since you thrust it aside and judge yourselves unworthy of eternal life, behold, we are turning to the Gentiles' — the pivotal programmatic declaration. The 'first to you' reflects the Christological mission order (Rom 1:16 — 'to the Jew first and also to the Greek'); the rejection by the synagogue leadership becomes the mechanism for the Gentile expansion. The Christological mission strategy is not Plan B — the Gentile inclusion was always the plan (Isa 49:6, cited in v. 47). The Jewish rejection does not defeat the plan; it triggers its next stage.</p>",
    "48": "<p>'And when the Gentiles heard this, they began rejoicing and glorifying the word of the Lord, and as many as were appointed to eternal life believed' (<em>hosoi ēsan tetagmenoi eis zōēn aiōnion episteusan</em>) — the Christological election vocabulary arrives: 'appointed to eternal life' is the divine prior ordination that belief expresses rather than creates. The Christological proclamation reveals who has been appointed — those appointed believe when they hear. The joy and glorifying is the Spirit's own response in those whose appointment is activated by the Christological word.</p>",
    "49": "<p>The word of the Lord spread through the whole region — the pattern of exponential expansion from a single synagogue proclamation to an entire geographic region is the Christological mission's consistent dynamic. The seed of the word produces harvest far beyond what the initial sowing could predict. Christ's own parable of the sower (Luke 8:4-15) described this precisely: the scattered word lands in prepared soil and produces a hundredfold return.</p>",
    "50": "<p>The devout women of high standing and the leading men of the city stirred up persecution against Paul and Barnabas and drove them out of the district. The Christological irony: the most religious and socially prominent members of the city become the instruments of persecution. Social status and religious reputation do not guarantee reception of the Christological message; often they correlate with resistance. The cross is 'a stumbling block to Jews and folly to Gentiles' (1 Cor 1:23) precisely for those whose religious or intellectual identity is most invested in alternative frameworks.</p>",
    "51": "<p>Paul and Barnabas shook the dust from their feet — the Christological gesture of repudiation (Luke 9:5; 10:11 — Jesus instructed his disciples to do this when rejected) — and went to Iconium. The gesture transfers moral responsibility to the rejecters; the missionaries have fulfilled their obligation. The Christological model: Jesus himself did not continue indefinitely in places of sustained rejection (Luke 13:34-35 — 'how often would I have gathered your children…'), and the pattern continues through his apostles.</p>",
    "52": "<p>'And the disciples were filled with joy and with the Holy Spirit' — the closing note on the Pisidian Antioch community after the apostles' expulsion is Christological testimony. The community that remained after Paul and Barnabas were driven out is filled with joy and the Spirit — not despite the persecution but within it. The Christological community's joy in suffering is the signature of the resurrection faith: 'Count it all joy when you meet trials of various kinds' (Jas 1:2). The Spirit who raised Christ sustains the joy of those who suffer for Christ.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'acts')
    merge_comm(existing, CHRIST)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH12)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH13)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'acts', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Acts mkt-christ: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
